Import & Settings¶

In [3]:
import ospgrillage as og

Units¶

Establish a consistent set of units - in this case the base units are N and m.

In [6]:
kilo = 1e3
milli = 1e-3
N = 1
m = 1
mm = milli * m
m2 = m ** 2
m3 = m ** 3
m4 = m ** 4
kN = kilo * N
Pa = 1
MPa = N / ((mm) ** 2)
GPa = kilo * MPa
kPa = kilo * Pa

Materials¶

Create a Material object using create_material() function.

In [7]:
concrete = og.create_material(material="concrete", code="AS5100-2017", grade="65MPa")

Alternatively, users can always create customize concrete material with:

  1. Elastic modulus, E
  2. Possion ratio, v
  3. Density, rho

If shear modulus, $G$, is not defined ospgrillage automatically determines the shear modulus using $ G = \frac{E}{2 (1+v)} $

In [8]:
concrete_custom = og.create_material(material="concrete",E=50*GPa, v= 0.3, rho=24*kN/m3 )

Grillage Members¶

Creating grillage members requires:

  1. Material object
  2. Section object
In [11]:
longitudinal_beam = og.create_member(section=longitudinal_section, material=concrete)

edge_longitudinal_beam = og.create_member(
    section=edge_longitudinal_section, material=concrete
)
transverse_slab = og.create_member(section=transverse_section, material=concrete)

end_transverse_slab = og.create_member(
    section=end_transverse_section, material=concrete
)

Bridge deck geometry¶

Here we define the span (L), width, (w) and skew angle of the edge (angle). In addition, we define the properties of the mesh i.e. number of longitudinal members (n_l) and transverse members (n_t) as well as the distance between the edge beam and first exterior beam (edge_dist).

In [12]:
display.Image(b64decode(cross_section_png))
Out[12]:
In [13]:
L = 33.5 * m                  # span
w = 11.565 * m                # width
n_l = 7                       # number of longitudinal members
n_t = 11                      # number of transverse members
edge_dist = 1.05 * m          # distance between edge beam and first exterior beam
ext_to_int_dist = 2.2775 * m  # distance between first exterior beam and first interior beam
angle = 0                     # skew angle

Create the Grillage Model¶

Creating model using create_grillage() function. Then assigning the defined GrillageMembers to the elements using set_member() function.

In [14]:
model = og.create_grillage(
    bridge_name="Super-T 33_5m",
    long_dim=L,
    width=w,
    skew=angle,
    num_long_grid=n_l,
    num_trans_grid=n_t,
    edge_beam_dist=edge_dist,
    ext_to_int_dist = ext_to_int_dist,
)

In ospgrillage, we set_member() using names for standard grillage element. For the standard non-skew bridge mesh, we set the :

In [15]:
# assign grillage member to element groups of grillage model
model.set_member(longitudinal_beam, member="interior_main_beam")
model.set_member(longitudinal_beam, member="exterior_main_beam_1")
model.set_member(longitudinal_beam, member="exterior_main_beam_2")
model.set_member(edge_longitudinal_beam, member="edge_beam")
model.set_member(transverse_slab, member="transverse_slab")
model.set_member(end_transverse_slab, member="start_edge")
model.set_member(end_transverse_slab, member="end_edge")

Last step, create the model in OpenSees using:

In [16]:
model.create_osp_model(pyfile=False)

Adding Load Case¶

From here, we will add load cases as defined in previous study of Caprani et al. (2017). We will detail the steps to create these load cases (e.g. dead load, and moving load models) in the following section.

In [19]:
display.Image(b64decode(table_png))
Out[19]:

(ref: Caprani et al. 2017)

Dead loads¶

Dead loads comprise of the self-weight of Super-T girders and overlay slab

For the comparison in this example, we shall split the Super-T girder and overlay slab's load cases into individual load cases.

Self-weight of Super-T girders¶

The self-weight of super-T girders is calculated as follows:

$ w_{girder} = 24 ~ \mathrm{kN/m^3} \times 0.934 ~ \mathrm{m^2} = 22.4 ~ \mathrm{kN/m} $

To this, we create a LineLoad and assign along position of longitudinal beams. Note for this example we assume this weight for all beams.

In [20]:
start_beam = 0
end_beam = L
beam_mag = 22.4 * kN / m

# create Super T self weight load case 
DL_self_weight = og.create_load_case(name="Super T self weight")

for z_pos in model.Mesh_obj.noz[1:-1]:
    beam_load_position_1 = og.create_load_vertex(x=start_beam, z=z_pos, p=beam_mag)
    beam_load_position_2 = og.create_load_vertex(x=end_beam, z=z_pos, p=beam_mag)

    self_weight_beam = og.create_load(loadtype="line", point1=beam_load_position_1, 
                                      point2=beam_load_position_2,)

    DL_self_weight.add_load(self_weight_beam)

model.add_load_case(DL_self_weight)

Overlay slab¶

A 180 mm in situ concrete overlay slab forms the deck. The distributed weight (area) of the deck is calculated as:

$ w_{slab} = 0.18 ~ \mathrm{m} \times 24 ~ \mathrm{kN/m^3} = 4.32 ~ \mathrm{kN/m^2} $

We use a PatchLoad to define the overlay slab weight.

In [21]:
overlay_p_mag = 4.32 * kN / m2 
patch_vertex_1 = og.create_load_vertex(x=0, z=0, p=overlay_p_mag)
patch_vertex_2 = og.create_load_vertex(x=L, z=0, p=overlay_p_mag)
patch_vertex_3 = og.create_load_vertex(x=L, z=w, p=overlay_p_mag)
patch_vertex_4 = og.create_load_vertex(x=0, z=w, p=overlay_p_mag)
                            
overlay_slab = og.create_load(
    loadtype="patch",
    name="overlay",
    point1=patch_vertex_1,
    point2=patch_vertex_2,
    point3=patch_vertex_3,
    point4=patch_vertex_4,
)

DL_overlay = og.create_load_case(name="Overlay self weight")
DL_overlay.add_load(overlay_slab)

model.add_load_case(DL_overlay)

Superimposed Dead loads (SIDL)¶

Superimposed dead load (SIDL) consist of asphalt surfacing and non-structural precast concrete edge barriers.

Asphalt surfacing¶

The surfacing is 65 mm thick with a self-weight of 22 kN/m$^3$

The magnitude of the asphalt surfacing is calculated as follows:

$ w_{asphalt} = 0.065 ~ \mathrm{m} \times 22 ~ \mathrm{kN/m^3} = 1.43 ~ \mathrm{kN/m^2} $

In [22]:
# asphalt surfacing (units kN/m2) - `patch` in global coords
asphalt_udl = 1.43 * kN / m2 

patch_vertex_1 = og.create_load_vertex(x=0, z=0, p=asphalt_udl)
patch_vertex_2 = og.create_load_vertex(x=L, z=0, p=asphalt_udl)
patch_vertex_3 = og.create_load_vertex(x=L, z=w, p=asphalt_udl)
patch_vertex_4 = og.create_load_vertex(x=0, z=w, p=asphalt_udl)
                            
asphalt_surfacing = og.create_load(
    loadtype="patch",
    name="asphat surfacing",
    point1=patch_vertex_1,
    point2=patch_vertex_2,
    point3=patch_vertex_3,
    point4=patch_vertex_4,
)

Precast edge barriers¶

The non-structural precast concrete edge barriers weighs 6.54 kN/m.

We use a line load to represent the precast edge barriers on the edge beams.

In [23]:
# precast edge barriers (units kN/m) - `compound` in global coords
barrier_udl = 6.54 * kN/m

left_barrier_p1 = og.create_load_vertex(x=0,z=0,p= barrier_udl)
left_barrier_p2 = og.create_load_vertex(x=L,z=0,p= barrier_udl)
right_barrier_p1 = og.create_load_vertex(x=0,z=w,p= barrier_udl)
right_barrier_p2 = og.create_load_vertex(x=L,z=w,p= barrier_udl)

left_barrier = og.create_load(
    loadtype="line", name="left barrier", point1=left_barrier_p1, point2=left_barrier_p2
)
right_barrier = og.create_load(
    loadtype="line", name="right barrier", point1=right_barrier_p1, point2=right_barrier_p2
)

Add both Asphalt and Parapets to a load case called SIDL

In [24]:
SIDL = og.create_load_case(name="SIDL")
SIDL.add_load(asphalt_surfacing)
SIDL.add_load(left_barrier)
SIDL.add_load(right_barrier)
model.add_load_case(SIDL)

Australian Traffic Load Model (M1600)¶

This is a 12-axle moving notional vehicle with central (variable) axle spacing set to 6.25 m and a uniformly distributed load on each standard design lane of 3.2 m (after AS 5100.2).

In [25]:
display.Image(b64decode(m1600_png))
Out[25]:

According to AS5100, the number of design lanes on bridge is:

$ n = \frac{33.5}{11.56} = 3.614 = 3 $

Thus, the gemoetric properties of the lanes relevant to the lane loading are:

In [26]:
# distance between lane edge and axle in z direction 
edge_dist = 0.6 * m 

# x and z coordinate of load model origin in global grillage coordinate
x_coord_L1 = 3.5 * m
z_coord_L1 = 1.8825 * m

x_coord_L2 = 3.5 * m
z_coord_L2 = 5.0825 * m

x_coord_L3 = 3.5 * m
z_coord_L3 = 8.2825 * m

x_coord = [x_coord_L1,x_coord_L2,x_coord_L3,]
z_coord = [z_coord_L1,z_coord_L2,z_coord_L3,]

Create the load case for M1600

In [27]:
M1600_load_case = og.create_load_case(name="M1600 notional")

Create M1600 vehicle¶

For this, we use ospgrillage's CompoundLoad object. Similar to the UDL component, we can adopt a for loop to generate the PointLoad of each axle then add to the compound load.

In [32]:
display.Image(b64decode(axle_top_png))
Out[32]:

Here, p1 is the 60 kN wheel load.

With ospgrillage, users can write generic functions that wraps the create_load() function. The following example showcase how we can create the axles using a function. Note for load models, ospgrillage v0.1.1 has an API function create_load_model() for this M1600 and other types of load model.

In [33]:
def make_M1600_vehicle(gap):
    """
    Makes an M1600 vehicle in local coordinates
    """
    axle_dist = 1.25 * m 
    left_group_dist = 3.75 * m 
    right_group_dist = 5 * m 
    wheel_load = 60*kN
    
    # Define longitudinal positions of each axle
    load_positions_x = [
        0,
        axle_dist,
        axle_dist * 2,
        left_group_dist + axle_dist * 2 ,
        left_group_dist+ axle_dist * 2  + axle_dist,
        left_group_dist + axle_dist * 2 +  2 * axle_dist,
        gap + left_group_dist + axle_dist * 2 +  2 * axle_dist ,
        gap + left_group_dist + axle_dist * 2 +  2 * axle_dist + axle_dist,
        gap + left_group_dist + axle_dist * 2 +  2 * axle_dist + axle_dist * 2,
        right_group_dist + gap + left_group_dist + axle_dist * 2 +  2 * axle_dist + axle_dist * 2 ,
        right_group_dist + gap + left_group_dist + axle_dist * 2 +  2 * axle_dist + axle_dist * 2  + axle_dist,
        right_group_dist + gap + left_group_dist + axle_dist * 2 +  2 * axle_dist + axle_dist * 2 +  2 * axle_dist,
    ]
    # Transverse position of each wheel
    load_positions_z = [-1, 1]
    
    M1600_vehicle = og.create_compound_load(name="M1600 Vehicle")
    for z in load_positions_z:
        for x in load_positions_x:
            vert = og.create_load_vertex(x=x, z=z, p=wheel_load)
            point = og.create_load(loadtype="point",name="M1600 point", point1 = vert)
            M1600_vehicle.add_load(load_obj=point)

    return M1600_vehicle

According to AS5100, the accompanying lane factor factors for the three design lanes (denoted as L1, L2 and L3) are 1.0, 0.8 and 0.4 respectively.

The dynamic allowance factor of 30% is defined here.

In [34]:
alf = [1.0, 0.8, 0.4]
dla = 1.3

And we'll also make a list of the elements that we will move

In [35]:
M1600_moving_loads = []

Now, create the M1600 load model for each lane comprising:

  • Vehicle
  • UDL patch load

We create a PatchLoad object and M1600 vehicle on each traffic lane, and add them into a single load case using a for loop:

In [36]:
gap = 6.25 * m 
m1600_L1_lc = og.create_load_case(name="M1600 L1")
m1600_L2_lc = og.create_load_case(name="M1600 L2")
m1600_L3_lc = og.create_load_case(name="M1600 L3")
m1600_lc_list = [m1600_L1_lc,m1600_L2_lc,m1600_L3_lc]

for i in range(3):
    # Create generic vehicle
    M1600_vehicle_generator = og.create_load_model(model_type="M1600",gap=gap)
    M1600_vehicle_n = M1600_vehicle_generator.create()
    # Position in global coords
    M1600_vehicle_n.set_global_coord(og.Point(x_coord[i], 0, z_coord[i]))
    # And add to the load case with the lane factor
    m1600_lc_list[i].add_load(load_obj=M1600_vehicle_n,load_factor=alf[i])
    # And store in list for moving load
    M1600_moving_loads.append(M1600_vehicle_n)
    
    # Now create the patch
    vertex_1 = og.create_load_vertex(x=-L, z=z_coord[i] - udl_width/2, p=udl_mag)
    vertex_2 = og.create_load_vertex(x=2*L, z=z_coord[i] - udl_width/2, p=udl_mag)
    vertex_3 = og.create_load_vertex(x=2*L, z=z_coord[i] + udl_width/2, p=udl_mag)
    vertex_4 = og.create_load_vertex(x=-L, z=z_coord[i] + udl_width/2, p=udl_mag)

    M1600_udl = og.create_load(
        loadtype="patch",
        name="M1600 Lane UDL",
        point1=vertex_1,
        point2=vertex_2,
        point3=vertex_3,
        point4=vertex_4,
    )
    m1600_lc_list[i].add_load(load_obj=M1600_udl,load_factor=alf[i])
    model.add_load_case(m1600_lc_list[i],load_factor=dla)

Finally, we add the defined M1600 lane loads to a load case named M1600_lc, then adding it to model and applying the dla to the load case.

Moving load case¶

We can make the M1600 into a moving load case instead.

For this example, lets move the M1600 starting from its initial (static load case) position to 4 meters in the x direction.

Create moving path¶

First we create a Path object for the load model. A path is defined using two Point named tuple defined either by create_point() or directly Point(x,y,z).

Since the origin of the truck compound load coordinate system is at the back axle $x_{local} = 0$ m, we need to place the start point at $x_{global}=-25 $ m and the end point at the end of the bridge.

In [37]:
start = og.create_point(x=-25,y=0,z=0)
end = og.Point(L,0,0)
m1600_path = og.create_moving_path(start_point=start, end_point= end)

Create moving load¶

Create moving load object; adding Path and Load components to moving load.

We do this using a for loop again. Since the load components of the M1600 have been previously created and stored in M1600_moving_loads, we can just add it to the moving load.

In [38]:
moving_load_list = []
for i in range(3):
    name = f"Moving M1600 L{i+1}"
    moving_m1600 = og.create_moving_load(name=name) 
    moving_m1600.set_path(m1600_path)
    moving_m1600.add_load(M1600_moving_loads[i])
    model.add_load_case(moving_m1600)
    #add to list for later on
    moving_load_list.append(moving_m1600)

The moving load is parsed into load cases for each incremental position in the path. The default increment is 50.

Structure of results¶

The results is a Xarray DataSet containing several DataArrays and Variables.

In [43]:
display.Image(b64decode(data_structure_png))
Out[43]:

To extract DataArray of displacement components:

In [44]:
static_lc_displacements = static_lc_result.displacements

To extract DataArray of force components:

In [45]:
static_lc_forces = static_lc_result.forces

Extract elements and nodes of Beam 1¶

Before we extract results of a Beam 1 (the "exterior_main_beam_1" of the model), we identify the elements and nodes of that grillage element.

With ospgrillage, we can query the element and node numbers using get_element() function and the name of standard element as defined previously during set_member() step.

In [46]:
member_name = "exterior_main_beam_1"

Now, get the tag of elements and nodes:

In [47]:
ext_beam_elements = model.get_element(member=member_name, options="elements",)
print(f"The element tags for Beam 1 is {ext_beam_elements}")

The element tags for Beam 1 is [20, 33, 46, 59, 72, 85, 98, 111, 124, 131]
In [48]:
ext_beam_nodes = model.get_element(member=member_name, options="nodes")
print(f"The node tags for Beam 1 is {ext_beam_nodes[0]}")

The node tags for Beam 1 is [2, 16, 23, 30, 37, 44, 51, 58, 65, 72, 9]

Selecting a specific load case from result¶

We extract for each load case and compare with values in Table 3 of Caprani et al. (2017).

In [49]:
load_case_name = ['M1600 L1','M1600 L2', 'M1600 L3']

We extract maximum bending moment of Beam 1 (member_name) from static_lc_forces as before:

In [50]:
max_bending = 0
for i in range(3):
    max_bending += max(static_lc_forces.sel(Loadcase=load_case_name[i],
                                              Component="Mz_i",Element=ext_beam_elements)).values/1000
print(f" Maximum bending moment = {max_bending:.2f} kNm") 

 Maximum bending moment = 5224.48 kNm
In [51]:
display.Image(b64decode(table_png))
Out[51]:

Plotting results¶

We can plot force and displacement components from results using plot_force() and plot_defo functions respectively.

Plot BMD and deflection for Beam 1 of Figure 1 (i.e. "exterior_main_beam_1" of model).

In [52]:
load_case_of_interest = load_case_name[0] # M1600 L1
og.plot_force(model, results, member="exterior_main_beam_1",component="Mz",loadcase=load_case_of_interest)

max_report_bending = f"Maximum bending moment = {max_bending:.2f} kNm"

og.plt.title(max_report_bending);

We can also plot for deflections. Here we plot the deflections for M1600 L1 load case

In [53]:
max_def = max(results.displacements.sel(Loadcase=load_case_name[0],Component="dy",Node=ext_beam_nodes[0]))
max_report_def = f"The maximum deflection = {max_def.values*1000:.2f} mm"

og.plot_defo(model, results, member="exterior_main_beam_1", option="nodes",loadcase=load_case_of_interest)
og.plt.title(max_report_def);

With this plotting feature, we can instantantly plot for various load cases in results.

Design SLS combination¶

Load combinations for AS5100 serviceability limit state (SLS) can be calculated from load case results as well.

The factors are 1.0, 1.0 and 1.3 for DL, Traffic, and SIDL load cases respectively.

In [54]:
DL_factor = 1.0
LL_factor = 1.0
SIDL_factor = 1.3

To get combinations, pass into the keywordcombinations= of get_results() function a dictionary with load case names as keys and corresponding load factors as values:

In [55]:
load_combinations = {'Super T self weight':DL_factor,
                     'M1600 L1':LL_factor,
                     'M1600 L2':LL_factor,
                     'M1600 L3':LL_factor,
                     'SIDL':SIDL_factor,
                     'Overlay self weight':DL_factor}

combination_results = model.get_results(combinations=load_combinations)
combination_results

Envelope¶

We can create envelope of the analysis results - via Envelope feature of the post-processing module.

We will showcase with getting envelopes for static load cases and then we consider moving load later on.

By using create_envelope() function and passing in static_lc_results, a reduced xarray (in the dimension on load case) is returned based on the specificed maxima (either "max" or "min").

Shell model¶

Next, we explore a modern model template available in ospgrillage - the Shell and Beam element model.

In [61]:
display.Image(b64decode(shell_beam_ideal_png))
Out[61]:

For this model we use the same properties for beam elements except this time we define Section properties of slab.

Define a slab depth:

In [62]:
slab_depth = 0.18 * m

Create a shell section - ospgrillage automatically detects this as shell when a cross-section depth, h is set.

In [63]:
slab_shell_section = og.create_section(h=slab_depth)

Create a grillage member then assigning the material and shell section

In [64]:
slab_shell = og.create_member(section=slab_shell_section, material=concrete)

Creating a new model call shell_model. Similar to traditional model, we set the members of the model.

In [65]:
shell_model = og.create_grillage(
    bridge_name="Super-T 33_5m",
    long_dim=L,
    width=w,
    skew=angle,
    num_long_grid=n_l,
    num_trans_grid=n_t,
    edge_beam_dist=edge_dist,
    model_type="shell_beam",
    max_mesh_size_z=1,
    max_mesh_size_x=1,
    offset_beam_y_dist=0.499,
    beam_width=0.89
)
In [66]:
# set beams
shell_model.set_member(longitudinal_beam, member="interior_main_beam")
shell_model.set_member(longitudinal_beam, member="exterior_main_beam_1")
shell_model.set_member(longitudinal_beam, member="exterior_main_beam_2")
# set shell
shell_model.set_shell_members(slab_shell)

Create the model in OpenSees

In [67]:
shell_model.create_osp_model(pyfile=False)

Plot the model using GetRendering - currently ops_vis is not able to visualize mix element model (shell + beam)

In [68]:
og.opsplt.plot_model("nodes");

No Model_ODB specified, trying to get data from the active model.
3D model

Now we simply add the previously defined load cases to shell model. Following this, we analyze the load cases.

In [69]:
shell_model.add_load_case(DL_self_weight)
shell_model.add_load_case(DL_overlay)
shell_model.add_load_case(SIDL)
for i in range(3):
    shell_model.add_load_case(m1600_lc_list[i])
    shell_model.add_load_case(moving_load_list[i])
